<br>
Reread that.  It's patently absurd.  Cows existed before they were domesticated.  To this day cows go feral and survive.<br>
<br>
Regarding the argument that humans are at the top of the food chain.<br>
<br>
The food chain is a logical construct that can be stuctured in any way one likes.  Bacteria, which eat human flesh, could be placed at the top.  Plants could be placed at the top instead of the bottom.  We just like to say we are at the top because we think the top superior and we made the damn chart.<br>
<br>
Regarding the argument that humans are omnivoires, always have been and that's just the way it is.  <br>
<br>
I'm assuming you live in a tree since homids are tree-dwellers, always have been and that's just the way it is.  How do you get internet access up there?<br>
<br>
Now, as to vegetarians as less cruel.<br>
<br>
Realise that vegetarianism is made possible largely by mass-agriculture.  It is also aided by chemical supplements.  In the developing world people usually survive on a diet consisting largely of vegetables withe meat substitutes.  Pure vegetarianism, and certainly vegainism is a product of western style agriculture.  Western style agriculture burns over nine caloeis of energy to produce one calorie of food.  This is only possible through the burning of fossil fuels in the agriculture process.  Which is less cruel?  Eating some animals or poisoning the entire biosphere?  What's better in the big picture?<br>
<br>
For myself, I'm still trying to figure out how to stem the horrible outbreak of humanity this planet is dying from. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/utzarothfv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tzaroth FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 546<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/24/02 3:35:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1430.topic&index=75>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Ok, I have to weigh in on the food chain</span><hr size=1> I'm pretty sure that it's been said before, but I don't really want to read through this entire thread. Why can't you just eat what you want to, and let other people do the same (provided that they aren't eating humans)? If they try to tell you that you that your eating ways are sinful and disgusting or whatnot, just roll your eyes in their general direction. But that goes both ways, too -- if veggies are their food of choice, so be it. It's no big deal. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umithlin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Mithlin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 41<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/24/02 7:53:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1430.topic&index=76>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Ok, I have to weigh in on the food chain</span><hr size=1> I have no problem with what people choose to eat.  I generally won't tease people about it either.  (Well, aside from ferverant vegans that are oppertunists and will eat meat if they need to, and playing the song quoted earlier in this thread to them in jest once)<br>
<br>
I am not a dietician.  I do not know what humans can and can't survive on.  I do know we are omnivores.  I also know we are animals.<br>
<br>
Now, I won't anthropromorphasize.  That is, I won't project human emotion onto animals.  But that doesn't mean I don't think they reason or feel.  And I can understand people trying to explain it in term of human emotions.  But I have watched animals long enough to notice they are each individuals.  But that doesn't really change anything.<br>
<br>
Suffering.  Yeah, they may suffer.  But for the most part humans are relatively nice in that regard.  Did you know a cheetah does not have very large teeth like other cats, and has to resort to biting it's preys throat and suffocating it to death?  Did you know an animal with a broken leg will be abandoned by it's mother despite plantive crys for help?  Did you know that many predators will start eating before their prey is completely dead?<br>
<br>
Cannibalism.  It makes sense.  What has all the nutrients you need?  Something like you does.  But while that may be, it has high risk.  Much more likely any disease could be passed on.  That is why it is not a bad idea.  Well, that and any number of social and otherwise non nutritional reasons.<br>
<br>
PETA, good idea taken too far.  I would even go so far as to classify them as nuts.  Any orginization that deals with animals has to worry about PETA.  This includes the zoos that have the best kept animals and veterinarian clinics.<br>
<br>
So I say eat meat, eat vegetables.  I've started cutting back on meat myself partly in respect of a partially vegetarian roommate, partly for dietary concerns.  Oh and the reason she is partly vegetarian is because her body needed nutrients from meat.  Not everyone is built the same.  Some can do vegetarian and be fine, some can do carnivore and be fine.  (Literally carnivore)  Some can use the Atkins diet (Being malnourished is a surefire way to lose weight) some would make themselves sick on it.  I will try to be respectful and not shove my meat eating in other peoples faces.  Hey, I enjoy a good salad as much as the next guy.  But I still enjoy going out for a good rare steak some times.  There is actually a Simpsons episode about vegetarians and living together where Lisa goes on a vegetarian rampage.  She then talks to Apoo and finds out he's vegan, won't even eat cheese, but he explains he doesn't hate her for it.  It's about acceptance.<br>
<br>
And regarding pets and vegetarians.  For some pets it works, for others it doesn't.  Often it is very difficult.  Dogs you can work a vegetarian diet but it is extremely difficult and it won't be the healthiest dog in the world.  Cats are actually obligate carnivores - they must have meat, end of story.<br>
<br>
And finally I leave you with one final thought.  Vegetarians eat vegetables.  What do humanitarians eat? <p>Mithlin Lussarrna<BR>
Rogue of 37 seasons<BR>
